    9475             : 
    9476           0 : // Class Call_expression.
    9477             : 
    9478             : // A Go function can be viewed in a couple of different ways.  The
    9479           0 : // code of a Go function becomes a backend function with parameters
    9480             : // whose types are simply the backend representation of the Go types.
    9481             : // If there are multiple results, they are returned as a backend
    9482             : // struct.
    9483             : 
    9484             : // However, when Go code refers to a function other than simply
    9485             : // calling it, the backend type of that function is actually a struct.
    9486             : // The first field of the struct points to the Go function code
    9487             : // (sometimes a wrapper as described below).  The remaining fields
    9488             : // hold addresses of closed-over variables.  This struct is called a
    9489             : // closure.
    9490             : 
    9491             : // There are a few cases to consider.
    9492             : 
    9493             : // A direct function call of a known function in package scope.  In
    9494             : // this case there are no closed-over variables, and we know the name
    9495             : // of the function code.  We can simply produce a backend call to the
    9496             : // function directly, and not worry about the closure.
    9497             : 
    9498             : // A direct function call of a known function literal.  In this case
    9499             : // we know the function code and we know the closure.  We generate the
    9500             : // function code such that it expects an additional final argument of
    9501             : // the closure type.  We pass the closure as the last argument, after
    9502             : // the other arguments.
    9503             : 
    9504             : // An indirect function call.  In this case we have a closure.  We
    9505             : // load the pointer to the function code from the first field of the
    9506             : // closure.  We pass the address of the closure as the last argument.
    9507             : 
    9508             : // A call to a method of an interface.  Type methods are always at
    9509             : // package scope, so we call the function directly, and don't worry
    9510             : // about the closure.
    9511             : 
    9512             : // This means that for a function at package scope we have two cases.
    9513             : // One is the direct call, which has no closure.  The other is the
    9514             : // indirect call, which does have a closure.  We can't simply ignore
    9515             : // the closure, even though it is the last argument, because that will
    9516             : // fail on targets where the function pops its arguments.  So when
    9517             : // generating a closure for a package-scope function we set the
    9518             : // function code pointer in the closure to point to a wrapper
    9519             : // function.  This wrapper function accepts a final argument that
    9520             : // points to the closure, ignores it, and calls the real function as a
    9521             : // direct function call.  This wrapper will normally be efficient, and
    9522             : // can often simply be a tail call to the real function.
    9523             : 
    9524             : // We don't use GCC's static chain pointer because 1) we don't need
    9525             : // it; 2) GCC only permits using a static chain to call a known
    9526             : // function, so we can't use it for an indirect call anyhow.  Since we
    9527             : // can't use it for an indirect call, we may as well not worry about
    9528             : // using it for a direct call either.
    9529             : 
    9530             : // We pass the closure last rather than first because it means that
    9531             : // the function wrapper we put into a closure for a package-scope
    9532             : // function can normally just be a tail call to the real function.
    9533             : 
    9534             : // For method expressions we generate a wrapper that loads the
    9535             : // receiver from the closure and then calls the method.  This
    9536             : // unfortunately forces reshuffling the arguments, since there is a
    9537             : // new first argument, but we can't avoid reshuffling either for
    9538             : // method expressions or for indirect calls of package-scope
    9539             : // functions, and since the latter are more common we reshuffle for
    9540             : // method expressions.
    9541             : 
    9542             : // Note that the Go code retains the Go types.  The extra final
    9543             : // argument only appears when we convert to the backend
    9544             : // representation.
    9545             : 
    9546             : // Traversal.
    9547             : 
    9548             : int
    9549             : Call_expression::do_traverse(Traverse* traverse)

    9551             :   // If we are calling a function in a different package that returns

    9557             :       Function_type *fntype = this->get_function_type();
